##Late at night, Wuhan Girl in the phone crying

Micro Signal Zhenshigushi1

Function description, every day a moving original true story.

What can ordinary people do to fight an epidemic? Zhang Xiao, who lives in Shandong Province, has signed up as an online volunteer to help people with suspected infections channel their fears and anxieties over the phone. She could hear the cries of the people of Wuhan in the dead of night, and she could feel the warmth of those in need.

Year: 2020

Location: Wuhan, Shandong
January 23 evening, my husband and I at home boiled mutton. On New Year's Day twenty-nine, the jubilant scene of Chinese New Year on TV is about to overflow the screen. My husband asked me what I want to eat tomorrow stuffing dumplings, I blurted out: LEEK MEAT! My husband smiled and said, I'm ready.
At that moment, the telephone rang. It was a friend who had rushed back to Huanggang before the city was shut down. We spoke on the phone this morning. He spoke in a hurried, flustered voice. Let me help him. The sound of laughter from the television, my husband and I announced, went to the balcony.
"What's going on? Don't panic. You take your time. "
He told me that a Shandong colleague named Linlin, about my age, had helped him many times. He had been in the crowd when he heard Linlin crying and losing it, and he was so worried that he wanted me to call Linlin and talk some sense into her.
After graduating from university, I do a primary school in Shandong psychological teachers, school teachers and students in charge of mental health. The school has set up a psychological counseling room, once students have psychological problems, I conduct counseling and follow-up records. Occasionally, a teacher would come over, and we'd talk, and we'd throw a few punches at a special puppet.
The friend says, know I am a psychology teacher, see if can pacify a bit. I asked about Linlin, and my friend told me that the one person she didn't have was scared in Wuhan. I got Linlin's contact information. Tell him not to worry.
There was a strong wind that night. There were not many people in the street, but there were many cars. On the eve of the Lunar New Year, people go all out to go home for a bite of hot reunion dinner. I called Linlin's number and waited a long time. I was about to hang up when a soft voice said, "hello, who is it? "
I quickly introduced myself, stressed that we are fellow villagers, want to chat with her, see if there is anything to help. Linlin didn't respond immediately. I told her that maybe, by some chance, we'd live close enough to visit her parents. After a moment of silence, she burst into conversation.
"I'm afraid, especially afraid, save me, I'm still young! " was followed by a burst of wailing. I knew there was a thread in her heart, and it snapped.
Linlin, afraid of trouble for his family, chose to stay in Huanggang, but was not ready to carry on. I said Yes to her first, then, since the family took the first step, it is to stick to, you parents here must worry, if not take care of themselves, parents know, not to throw away all their efforts.
Linlin's cry grew smaller and smaller, and I let out a long breath. She just needs someone to calm her down and tell her it's okay.
Linlin told me that she is an old girl, her parents are old, many hearts do not dare to say to their parents, there are no friends, can only hold in the stomach, too many things, easy to collapse. It's a good thing I called her, otherwise I might have done something rash.
Picture | Linlin's bedroom window
Two days later, I joined an online volunteer organization that provides counseling to people in Wuhan and other cities in Hubei Province. I know, epidemic like a storm, doctors, nurses in the eye of the storm, the front of every move, touch the nerve of all people. Anxiety, disease, depression, and fear, which pervade social networks, can spread as fast as a virus, and without the right intervention, can lead to widespread panic.
In the early hours of January 25, I found an online organization that was looking for volunteers and filled out an application. There is a question in the application form: "Why do you want to join? " Before the basic information, to this, I hesitated. Make a contribution to Wuhan. That was the first thing I could think of.
After half an hour, I was pulled into a wechat group of more than 200 people. I was friended and introduced myself as Miao Miao, a group leader, who asked if I would like to join her group.
Miao Miao pulled me into a small group of ten. She sent me some papers to familiarize me with the volunteer process and prepare me for the next step. It was after 1:00 a.m.
The next morning, I opened the file and took notes as I read.
Before this, all I knew was that the cough and fever were symptoms of the new pneumonia, and I didn't know there was a hierarchy. It details criteria for mild and severe cases, blood oxygen levels, breathing rates, and access to medical resources.
In addition, the file also has the patient psychological analysis, including the patient's psychological characteristics, psychological care strategies and counseling hotline. When a patient is isolated at home alone, loneliness can amplify the panic, and in addition to practical help, the most important thing is care.
The online volunteers were treated by self-quarantined patients at home, screened by front-line doctors and local volunteers in Hubei Province. The person in charge assigned the patient data to the group, and the Group leader assigned it to us. After receiving the information, each online volunteer communicated with the patient, or family, by telephone.
After knowing the patient's condition, we choose the corresponding doctor according to the severity of the illness for them, and carry on the online consultation. If the situation is serious, contact the local volunteers to solve the oxygen machine and the corresponding drug problems, and then follow-up with each patient, return visit, fill in the record form.
Miao Miao told me, before communicating with patients, be sure to double check your status. Don't call a patient if you haven't reached 100. You've been a psychologist, I believe you.
I'll take two deep breaths and say, "I'm ready. ".
"Hello, I am a volunteer of the doctor team on the new Crown Action Line, you can call me Xiao, we received your form, inquire about your current situation, how do you call it? "
There was a lot of noise on the other end of the line, and I repeated it again, but there was no response. I thought she didn't hear me, but I cleared my throat and was ready to say it again, when I heard a husky voice, "hello... this is Li Xuan. I've just had a fever of 102. I have a cough and a bad appetite. "
"Do you have a confirmed or suspected patient? "
This time she replied quickly: "My old and old two (Mom and Dad) are confirmed to pull the hospital, I began the day before yesterday fever. "
On the morning of Jan. 29, I added Li Xuan's wechat account, sent a confirmation, received the signature, and pulled her into a counseling group, telling her to ask a doctor for advice on how to administer the medicine. She posted a thank you face. Of the eight patients contacted that day, Li Xuan's condition was not serious. I got up and poured a glass of water and rubbed my temples with my hands.
At 5:00 p.m. , I was filling out a tracking form, and Wechat rang. It was Li Xuan. "Your doctor is irresponsible and wants to kill me! Forget it! " She shouted in her voice. "Old Terry and the two doctors have been diagnosed. I have pneumonia. I know for a fact that your doctor says I have a cold
In my first few days as an online volunteer, I didn't know anything about quarantines. Despite his experience as a psychology teacher, the situation is far from perfect. I believe what the patient says, and the conversation tends to follow their train of thought, leading off course if they're not careful.
Then the doctor and a professional psychologist gave us a training. They said that some patients'conditions are not serious and they often exaggerate their condition on the phone due to their panic and wish to see a doctor as soon as possible. Another is as a close contact, once they have similar symptoms, you're pessimistic, you're scared to death. Li Xuan is one of the latter.
I called the doctor first to check on Li Xuan. According to the doctor's online diagnosis, she's not a symptom of NCP. I snort twice, dial her number. The telephone is connected, opposite is a burst of interspersed with the cough voice, the storm is like to scold. I don't talk back, go along with her words, try to comfort her, let her calm down. Half an hour later, she stopped screaming, and, judging by her voice, she had no strength left. I told her to have a glass of water, to sit down, and to take a deep breath.
"How do you feel? Why don't you lie down? You used a lot of energy just now. Just slow down. "
And then there was a cough. I said: "We wechat Chat, you type, do not speak. Otherwise the cough will be more serious. "
Hang up the phone. Let Li Xuan tell the story of her parents and her. After a moment of silence, she talked.
Li Xuan, a native of Hebei Province who lives with her parents in Wuhan and turned twenty-four this year, has always depended on them and stayed with them from childhood to adulthood. In December, she heard a colleague mention pneumonia, but the news was unconfirmed. On January 20, a friend from Hebei called and told her to go home with her parents for the New Year. Li Xuan laughed and Said No, reassuring his friends that it was all just a rumor. The people of Wuhan didn't even wear masks. They visited relatives, friends, parties, and shops, and were not affected in the least.
On New Year's Eve, at nine in the morning, Li Xuan was awakened by a sharp knock on the door. She rubbed her eyes and reluctantly opened the door. Mother came into the House, face anxious: "Xuan, you see the news, closed the city! "
Her mother's words poured cold water on Li Xuan, who sobered up for a moment and grabbed the phone. Wuhan closed the city, bus, subway, ferry, long-distance passenger transport suspended operations, the airport, trains are also closed from the Han Channel.
Her eyes glaze over as she sits on the couch, unaware that her phone has slipped. My mother was about to call for her when she was interrupted by a fit of coughing. Li Xuan recovered himself and went straight to his father's room. That afternoon, the father coughed and had a high fever of 39 degrees, which made it difficult to breathe. She left her mother at home and took him to the hospital herself. Three days later, the father was diagnosed and admitted to the hospital on January 27.
Her mother was admitted to the hospital an hour before she spoke to me.
In her twenty-four plus years, she had never experienced anything like this. In the past, when things went wrong, her parents always got in front of her. And now, without her umbrella, she panicked. I expressed my understanding to her, and said some words of encouragement and comfort.
In fact, these words are just seasoning, more importantly, a vent, the person on the other side of the phone did not give up and her communication. Li Xuan and I established effective communication and eventually trust. Later I call, she no longer said that he is pneumonia, according to the doctor's orders, adhere to take temperature, on time to take medicine, but also ask me to learn to cook.
On February 4, Li Xuan's fever finally broke.
Li Xuan's cooking
On Feb. 2, I called Le Le For the first time, and before I could finish the introduction, the 14 year old eighth grader interrupted me in a hurried voice, mixed with a cry: "My mother is very serious, need to go to the hospital, the community said there is no vehicle, wait any longer my mother will die, please, help me! "
It had been a week since I'd joined the online volunteer team, and with the countless phone calls I'd made, I'd become adept at judging the severity of my condition by the tone of voice, the speed of speech, the breath. But this is the first time I've met someone like Le LE.
I tried to calm her down. She needed to make contact with the community. Hang up the phone, I quickly find the community phone table, find the number to dial, the phone has been tip is in the call, I am impatient, lift his foot to the wall, pain clench teeth.
It wasn't until the fourth call that I finally got through. I explained the situation to the community, and I was told that the traffic was very tight, so I had to wait.
I posted about Le Le in the group and asked for your help. Miao Miao told me to call the hotline, and I called it in, but I was told there was nothing I could do. With a sigh, I called Le Le Again. Le Le Answered, "sister, what can I do? My mother was almost out of breath. "
I didn't know what to say in the face of Le Le's expectations. Le Le was smart enough to sense something, and she burst into tears. I encouraged her, but to no avail, she was so absorbed in her grief that she couldn't hear me.
It just occurred to me that teaching a sixth-grade girl at school. At that time, she was crying, ignoring my existence. I knew there was nothing I could say, so I turned on my computer, found a soothing piece of music, turned it up as loud as I could, and aimed it at the receiver.
When I was in college, my teacher said that the right kind of music could relieve emotional tension, divert attention, and even create empathy. With Le LE, it's just a matter of trying. It worked, and the music started playing, and Le Le's cry actually faded away.
"You listen to me, don't worry too much, the community car to send other patients, you have a lot of aunts and uncles also need to go to the hospital, after they will come to pick up your mother, don't cry, your mother will be very sad to hear, don't be afraid, I have been here. "
Le Le Sobbed and thanked me.
Three hours later, Le Le called and her mother was taken to the hospital. The house was empty, as if the world had abandoned her. I said, "when I was your age, I didn't know how to do anything. I was a coward. You were so much braver than me
This aroused the curiosity of Le Le, she asked: "really? Sister you are really very timid? "
I told Le Le The embarrassing story of my junior year. Cold Winter, my mother to visit, late, I learned the appearance of the TV series, go to the door waiting for my mother, but I underestimated their courage. My home to the gate, there are more than ten minutes of road, at that time, the community has no street lights, in the dark night, I shiver, grass from time to time from the slightest sound, I hug his arms, fast forward, the grass in the sound of more and more loud, I screamed, in tears, a cat jumped out and ran away with a yelp.
Le Le told me that she gets a lot of awards and does better when she's not afraid of anything.
I had Le Le Take her temperature regularly, sterilize her regularly, and as a close contact, I was afraid she might be infected, too. I then contacted the community volunteers and explained about Le Le, who said they would visit regularly. When I told Le Le About it, she wasn't happy.
"Don't you ever call me again? I wish I had a sister like you. "
Her voice sounded Husky, and my heart felt as if it were being held in one hand.
"My sister won't leave you. Now my sister has to contact other people who need help. I'll call you when I'm done, okay? "
Le Le Was satisfied with her answer, and she insisted that she be called.
Le Le's thank you note
For 20 days in a row, I called 311 phone numbers in Hubei, most of them in Wuhan, and each suspected patient had to make at least two calls, many even seven or eight, with 311 storm homes behind them.
I find myself really caring about people I've never met. I need to know if they're eating or not, what their temperature is, whether they're taking their meds or not, even if there's not a blank chart. I know their bodies, I know their interests, I know what they like to eat, I know what they like to watch, and I can no longer see them as strangers.
Later, I would call Le Le Every day, sometimes late, and she would text me. She said she'd see me when the epidemic was over.
- END -

Occasionally, a teacher would come over, and we'd talk, and we'd throw a few punches at a special puppet.

The friend says, know I am a psychology teacher, see if can pacify a bit. I asked about Linlin, and my friend told me that the one person she didn't have was scared in Wuhan. I got Linlin's contact information. Tell him not to worry.

There was a strong wind that night. There were not many people in the street, but there were many cars. On the eve of the Lunar New Year, people go all out to go home for a bite of hot reunion dinner. I called Linlin's number and waited a long time. I was about to hang up when a soft voice said, "hello, who is it? "

I quickly introduced myself, stressed that we are fellow villagers, want to chat with her, see if there is anything to help. Linlin didn't respond immediately. I told her that maybe, by some chance, we'd live close enough to visit her parents. After a moment of silence, she burst into conversation.

"I'm afraid, especially afraid, save me, I'm still young! " was followed by a burst of wailing. I knew there was a thread in her heart, and it snapped.

Linlin, afraid of trouble for his family, chose to stay in Huanggang, but was not ready to carry on. I said Yes to her first, then, since the family took the first step, it is to stick to, you parents here must worry, if not take care of themselves, parents know, not to throw away all their efforts.

Linlin's cry grew smaller and smaller, and I let out a long breath. She just needs someone to calm her down and tell her it's okay.

Linlin told me that she is an old girl, her parents are old, many hearts do not dare to say to their parents, there are no friends, can only hold in the stomach, too many things, easy to collapse. It's a good thing I called her, otherwise I might have done something rash.

Picture | Linlin's bedroom window

Two days later, I joined an online volunteer organization that provides counseling to people in Wuhan and other cities in Hubei Province. I know, epidemic like a storm, doctors, nurses in the eye of the storm, the front of every move, touch the nerve of all people. Anxiety, disease, depression, and fear, which pervade social networks, can spread as fast as a virus, and without the right intervention, can lead to widespread panic.

In the early hours of January 25, I found an online organization that was looking for volunteers and filled out an application. There is a question in the application form: "Why do you want to join? " Before the basic information, to this, I hesitated. Make a contribution to Wuhan. That was the first thing I could think of.

After half an hour, I was pulled into a wechat group of more than 200 people. I was friended and introduced myself as Miao Miao, a group leader, who asked if I would like to join her group.

Miao Miao pulled me into a small group of ten. She sent me some papers to familiarize me with the volunteer process and prepare me for the next step. It was after 1:00 a.m.

The next morning, I opened the file and took notes as I read.

Before this, all I knew was that the cough and fever were symptoms of the new pneumonia, and I didn't know there was a hierarchy. It details criteria for mild and severe cases, blood oxygen levels, breathing rates, and access to medical resources.

In addition, the file also has the patient psychological analysis, including the patient's psychological characteristics, psychological care strategies and counseling hotline. When a patient is isolated at home alone, loneliness can amplify the panic, and in addition to practical help, the most important thing is care.

The online volunteers were treated by self-quarantined patients at home, screened by front-line doctors and local volunteers in Hubei Province. The person in charge assigned the patient data to the group, and the Group leader assigned it to us. After receiving the information, each online volunteer communicated with the patient, or family, by telephone.

After knowing the patient's condition, we choose the corresponding doctor according to the severity of the illness for them, and carry on the online consultation. If the situation is serious, contact the local volunteers to solve the oxygen machine and the corresponding drug problems, and then follow-up with each patient, return visit, fill in the record form.

Miao Miao told me, before communicating with patients, be sure to double check your status. Don't call a patient if you haven't reached 100. You've been a psychologist, I believe you.

I'll take two deep breaths and say, "I'm ready. ".

"Hello, I am a volunteer of the doctor team on the new Crown Action Line, you can call me Xiao, we received your form, inquire about your current situation, how do you call it? "

There was a lot of noise on the other end of the line, and I repeated it again, but there was no response. I thought she didn't hear me, but I cleared my throat and was ready to say it again, when I heard a husky voice, "hello... this is Li Xuan. I've just had a fever of 102. I have a cough and a bad appetite. "

"Do you have a confirmed or suspected patient? "

This time she replied quickly: "My old and old two (Mom and Dad) are confirmed to pull the hospital, I began the day before yesterday fever. "

On the morning of Jan. 29, I added Li Xuan's wechat account, sent a confirmation, received the signature, and pulled her into a counseling group, telling her to ask a doctor for advice on how to administer the medicine. She posted a thank you face. Of the eight patients contacted that day, Li Xuan's condition was not serious. I got up and poured a glass of water and rubbed my temples with my hands.

At 5:00 p.m. , I was filling out a tracking form, and Wechat rang. It was Li Xuan. "Your doctor is irresponsible and wants to kill me! Forget it! " She shouted in her voice. "Old Terry and the two doctors have been diagnosed. I have pneumonia. I know for a fact that your doctor says I have a cold

In my first few days as an online volunteer, I didn't know anything about quarantines. Despite his experience as a psychology teacher, the situation is far from perfect. I believe what the patient says, and the conversation tends to follow their train of thought, leading off course if they're not careful.

Then the doctor and a professional psychologist gave us a training. They said that some patients'conditions are not serious and they often exaggerate their condition on the phone due to their panic and wish to see a doctor as soon as possible. Another is as a close contact, once they have similar symptoms, you're pessimistic, you're scared to death. Li Xuan is one of the latter.

I called the doctor first to check on Li Xuan. According to the doctor's online diagnosis, she's not a symptom of NCP. I snort twice, dial her number. The telephone is connected, opposite is a burst of interspersed with the cough voice, the storm is like to scold. I don't talk back, go along with her words, try to comfort her, let her calm down. Half an hour later, she stopped screaming, and, judging by her voice, she had no strength left. I told her to have a glass of water, to sit down, and to take a deep breath.

"How do you feel? Why don't you lie down? You used a lot of energy just now. Just slow down. "

And then there was a cough. I said: "We wechat Chat, you type, do not speak. Otherwise the cough will be more serious. "

Hang up the phone. Let Li Xuan tell the story of her parents and her. After a moment of silence, she talked.

Li Xuan, a native of Hebei Province who lives with her parents in Wuhan and turned twenty-four this year, has always depended on them and stayed with them from childhood to adulthood. In December, she heard a colleague mention pneumonia, but the news was unconfirmed. On January 20, a friend from Hebei called and told her to go home with her parents for the New Year. Li Xuan laughed and Said No, reassuring his friends that it was all just a rumor. The people of Wuhan didn't even wear masks. They visited relatives, friends, parties, and shops, and were not affected in the least.

On New Year's Eve, at nine in the morning, Li Xuan was awakened by a sharp knock on the door. She rubbed her eyes and reluctantly opened the door. Mother came into the House, face anxious: "Xuan, you see the news, closed the city! "

Her mother's words poured cold water on Li Xuan, who sobered up for a moment and grabbed the phone. Wuhan closed the city, bus, subway, ferry, long-distance passenger transport suspended operations, the airport, trains are also closed from the Han Channel.

Her eyes glaze over as she sits on the couch, unaware that her phone has slipped. My mother was about to call for her when she was interrupted by a fit of coughing. Li Xuan recovered himself and went straight to his father's room. That afternoon, the father coughed and had a high fever of 39 degrees, which made it difficult to breathe. She left her mother at home and took him to the hospital herself. Three days later, the father was diagnosed and admitted to the hospital on January 27.

Her mother was admitted to the hospital an hour before she spoke to me.

In her twenty-four plus years, she had never experienced anything like this. In the past, when things went wrong, her parents always got in front of her. And now, without her umbrella, she panicked. I expressed my understanding to her, and said some words of encouragement and comfort.

In fact, these words are just seasoning, more importantly, a vent, the person on the other side of the phone did not give up and her communication. Li Xuan and I established effective communication and eventually trust. Later I call, she no longer said that he is pneumonia, according to the doctor's orders, adhere to take temperature, on time to take medicine, but also ask me to learn to cook.

On February 4, Li Xuan's fever finally broke.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Li Xuan's cooking

On Feb. 2, I called Le Le For the first time, and before I could finish the introduction, the 14 year old eighth grader interrupted me in a hurried voice, mixed with a cry: "My mother is very serious, need to go to the hospital, the community said there is no vehicle, wait any longer my mother will die, please, help me! "

It had been a week since I'd joined the online volunteer team, and with the countless phone calls I'd made, I'd become adept at judging the severity of my condition by the tone of voice, the speed of speech, the breath. But this is the first time I've met someone like Le LE.

I tried to calm her down. She needed to make contact with the community. Hang up the phone, I quickly find the community phone table, find the number to dial, the phone has been tip is in the call, I am impatient, lift his foot to the wall, pain clench teeth.

It wasn't until the fourth call that I finally got through. I explained the situation to the community, and I was told that the traffic was very tight, so I had to wait.

I posted about Le Le in the group and asked for your help. Miao Miao told me to call the hotline, and I called it in, but I was told there was nothing I could do. With a sigh, I called Le Le Again. Le Le Answered, "sister, what can I do? My mother was almost out of breath. "

I didn't know what to say in the face of Le Le's expectations. Le Le was smart enough to sense something, and she burst into tears. I encouraged her, but to no avail, she was so absorbed in her grief that she couldn't hear me.

It just occurred to me that teaching a sixth-grade girl at school. At that time, she was crying, ignoring my existence. I knew there was nothing I could say, so I turned on my computer, found a soothing piece of music, turned it up as loud as I could, and aimed it at the receiver.

When I was in college, my teacher said that the right kind of music could relieve emotional tension, divert attention, and even create empathy. With Le LE, it's just a matter of trying. It worked, and the music started playing, and Le Le's cry actually faded away.

"You listen to me, don't worry too much, the community car to send other patients, you have a lot of aunts and uncles also need to go to the hospital, after they will come to pick up your mother, don't cry, your mother will be very sad to hear, don't be afraid, I have been here. "

Le Le Sobbed and thanked me.

Three hours later, Le Le called and her mother was taken to the hospital. The house was empty, as if the world had abandoned her. I said, "when I was your age, I didn't know how to do anything. I was a coward. You were so much braver than me

This aroused the curiosity of Le Le, she asked: "really? Sister you are really very timid? "

I told Le Le The embarrassing story of my junior year. Cold Winter, my mother to visit, late, I learned the appearance of the TV series, go to the door waiting for my mother, but I underestimated their courage. My home to the gate, there are more than ten minutes of road, at that time, the community has no street lights, in the dark night, I shiver, grass from time to time from the slightest sound, I hug his arms, fast forward, the grass in the sound of more and more loud, I screamed, in tears, a cat jumped out and ran away with a yelp.

Le Le told me that she gets a lot of awards and does better when she's not afraid of anything.

I had Le Le Take her temperature regularly, sterilize her regularly, and as a close contact, I was afraid she might be infected, too. I then contacted the community volunteers and explained about Le Le, who said they would visit regularly. When I told Le Le About it, she wasn't happy.

"Don't you ever call me again? I wish I had a sister like you. "

Her voice sounded Husky, and my heart felt as if it were being held in one hand.

"My sister won't leave you. Now my sister has to contact other people who need help. I'll call you when I'm done, okay? "

Le Le Was satisfied with her answer, and she insisted that she be called.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Le Le's thank you note

For 20 days in a row, I called 311 phone numbers in Hubei, most of them in Wuhan, and each suspected patient had to make at least two calls, many even seven or eight, with 311 storm homes behind them.

I find myself really caring about people I've never met. I need to know if they're eating or not, what their temperature is, whether they're taking their meds or not, even if there's not a blank chart. I know their bodies, I know their interests, I know what they like to eat, I know what they like to watch, and I can no longer see them as strangers.

Later, I would call Le Le Every day, sometimes late, and she would text me. She said she'd see me when the epidemic was over.

- END -

By Xiao Zhang
